You know, the-- in that movie?

00:40:45.454 --> 00:40:46.620
ALAN CUMMING: In what movie?

00:40:46.620 --> 00:40:48.036
MICHAEL RAUCH: You
were, like, a--

00:40:48.036 --> 00:40:51.010
because I want you to do
that now, after "Macbeth."

00:40:51.010 --> 00:40:52.160
You did that cartoon--

00:40:52.160 --> 00:40:52.970
you know, you, uh--

00:40:52.970 --> 00:40:53.892
I'll remember it.

00:40:53.892 --> 00:40:54.850
Onto the next question.

00:40:54.850 --> 00:40:55.350
ALAN CUMMING: On my shoulder?

00:40:55.350 --> 00:40:56.050
MICHAEL RAUCH: It was so funny.

00:40:56.050 --> 00:40:56.550
No, no, no.

00:40:56.550 --> 00:40:57.444
It was in a movie.

00:40:57.444 --> 00:40:58.860
ALAN CUMMING: Oh,
the Great Gazoo.

00:40:58.860 --> 00:41:00.470
MICHAEL RAUCH: Great Gazoo, yes.

00:41:00.470 --> 00:41:02.520
Going to go from Lady
Macbeth to the Great Gazoo.

00:41:02.520 --> 00:41:03.490
ALAN CUMMING: Oh, what was he--

00:41:03.490 --> 00:41:04.460
MICHAEL RAUCH: The
range of Alan Cumming.

00:41:04.460 --> 00:41:05.270
ALAN CUMMING: Yeah,
what was it, again?

00:41:05.270 --> 00:41:06.250
Like, dum-dums.

00:41:06.250 --> 00:41:08.410
It was probably dum-dums, yeah.

00:41:08.410 --> 00:41:11.771
A range.

00:41:11.771 --> 00:41:12.770
MISTRAL MYERS: Go ahead.

00:41:12.770 --> 00:41:13.311
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:41:13.311 --> 00:41:15.090
Thank you both for being here.

00:41:15.090 --> 00:41:16.910
My question is actually
very much related

00:41:16.910 --> 00:41:22.050
to the previous one, but
I'll go one step further.

00:41:22.050 --> 00:41:24.140
So, the pilot introduces
the lead character

00:41:24.140 --> 00:41:27.230
as this mysterious guy,
but paradoxically we

00:41:27.230 --> 00:41:28.910
see a lot of him.

00:41:28.910 --> 00:41:30.780
I mean, a lot about his life.

00:41:30.780 --> 00:41:32.810
We know that he
works for the CIA.

00:41:32.810 --> 00:41:34.490
And we also know
that he's happily

00:41:34.490 --> 00:41:39.080
married to a man, which I feel
like in a regular TV show,

00:41:39.080 --> 00:41:42.440
that fact would stay
hidden for a bit longer.

00:41:42.440 --> 00:41:45.560
So is the lead character
really that mysterious?

00:41:45.560 --> 00:41:50.900
How much more should we
expect from the next episodes?

00:41:50.900 --> 00:41:54.910
I must admit that I haven't
read the novels, so, I'll--

00:41:54.910 --> 00:41:55.730
yeah.

00:41:55.730 --> 00:41:58.630
ALAN CUMMING: One in every 17
readers in America has, but--

00:42:02.150 --> 00:42:04.940
well, I mean, I think--

00:42:04.940 --> 00:42:05.720
it's a pilot.

00:42:05.720 --> 00:42:08.570
You've got to, like, say as much
as you can about the characters

00:42:08.570 --> 00:42:09.680
to get people interested.

00:42:09.680 --> 00:42:10.110
You know what I mean?

00:42:10.110 --> 00:42:11.276
So he's not that mysterious.

00:42:11.276 --> 00:42:12.640
You know a lot about him.

00:42:12.640 --> 00:42:13.820
But that's what pilots are.

00:42:13.820 --> 00:42:18.380
That's how you--
otherwise, you might not--

00:42:18.380 --> 00:42:22.270
you've got to, like, fling
stuff at the audience a bit.

00:42:22.270 --> 00:42:23.300
But the thing I think--

00:42:23.300 --> 00:42:28.750
and I guess we do know, and in
a broad way, all these facets.

00:42:28.750 --> 00:42:30.500
But actually, like,
you know, I was saying

00:42:30.500 --> 00:42:31.340
that thing about the hen.

00:42:31.340 --> 00:42:32.340
That's, for me, it's hilarious.

00:42:32.340 --> 00:42:34.048
Like, I suddenly get
a script and go, oh,

00:42:34.048 --> 00:42:36.560
I was once in Hong Kong
doing a blah, blah.

00:42:36.560 --> 00:42:39.635
That part of it, I think,
there's much more in.

00:42:39.635 --> 00:42:42.300
And there's also actually
more about his family

00:42:42.300 --> 00:42:45.604
that you don't know yet.

00:42:45.604 --> 00:42:48.020
The good thing about having
so many different facets, even

00:42:48.020 --> 00:42:51.890
though you kind of show
your cards a little,

00:42:51.890 --> 00:42:58.070
is that there's a wider or
a bigger suite to go to.

00:42:58.070 --> 00:43:03.800
But yeah, I think
that his mystery isn't

00:43:03.800 --> 00:43:06.315
that he's got hidden depths.

00:43:06.315 --> 00:43:07.940
Would you say, Michael,
as the creator?

00:43:07.940 --> 00:43:08.898
MICHAEL RAUCH: I agree.

00:43:08.898 --> 00:43:11.542
I'd also say that, although
you in the audience know it,

00:43:11.542 --> 00:43:12.500
the cops don't know it.

00:43:12.500 --> 00:43:14.750
So everyone he's working
with doesn't know his past,

00:43:14.750 --> 00:43:16.610
doesn't know he worked
for the CIA, which

00:43:16.610 --> 00:43:19.130
obviously would change their
perception of him enormously.

00:43:19.130 --> 00:43:21.505
So that's something that we
play with in terms of keeping

00:43:21.505 --> 00:43:22.580
the secret from them.

00:43:22.580 --> 00:43:24.320
And Lizzie getting
involved in that

00:43:24.320 --> 00:43:27.865
also, because I think that
her boss, the lieutenant,

00:43:27.865 --> 00:43:29.990
would have a very different
take on the information

00:43:29.990 --> 00:43:31.850
they're getting
if she knew where

00:43:31.850 --> 00:43:32.957
they were getting it from.

00:43:32.957 --> 00:43:34.790
AUDIENCE: It was such
a privilege seeing you

00:43:34.790 --> 00:43:39.230
in "Macbeth," and I'd love
to see you on stage again.

00:43:39.230 --> 00:43:41.780
Is there a project that
you have coming up,

00:43:41.780 --> 00:43:44.420
and/or is there something that
you're really eyeing to play

00:43:44.420 --> 00:43:46.392
in the future on Broadway?

00:43:46.392 --> 00:43:47.850
ALAN CUMMING: I
mean, we're waiting

00:43:47.850 --> 00:43:49.040
to see if this goes again.

00:43:49.040 --> 00:43:54.410
So that kind of makes my long
term planning rather difficult.

00:43:54.410 --> 00:43:58.920
So if that's the case, then we'd
start shooting again in July.

00:43:58.920 --> 00:44:00.470
But I do my concerts.

00:44:00.470 --> 00:44:02.870
Like I'm doing a new
show called "Alan

00:44:02.870 --> 00:44:05.396
Cumming, Legal Immigrant."

00:44:05.396 --> 00:44:06.770
It's sort of like
a cabaret show.

00:44:06.770 --> 00:44:09.103
My last one was called "Alan
Cumming Sings Sappy Songs."

00:44:09.103 --> 00:44:11.990
And I'm doing a really
great thing, actually.

00:44:11.990 --> 00:44:15.200
We're doing some shows on
tour, but then in June we're

00:44:15.200 --> 00:44:18.260
doing two weeks
here in New York.

00:44:18.260 --> 00:44:20.630
Because with the
last show, I began it

00:44:20.630 --> 00:44:23.600
at the Cafe Carlyle,
which is an amazing sort

00:44:23.600 --> 00:44:27.830
of historical cabaret
space to play at,

00:44:27.830 --> 00:44:29.810
but it's very expensive.

00:44:29.810 --> 00:44:31.879
And then we did Carnegie
Hall, which is also,

00:44:31.879 --> 00:44:33.170
of course, an incredible thing.

00:44:33.170 --> 00:44:34.730
But I was just like,
none of my friends

00:44:34.730 --> 00:44:36.688
can afford to come and
see me doing this thing.

00:44:36.688 --> 00:44:39.080
So I finished it in
December at Joe's Pub,

00:44:39.080 --> 00:44:41.079
and we did a few
nights at Joe's Pub.

00:44:41.079 --> 00:44:43.120
So now, with the new one,
with "Legal Immigrant,"

00:44:43.120 --> 00:44:45.036
I'm doing this great
thing-- and I can't quite

00:44:45.036 --> 00:44:47.750
believe they let me-- is
that we're doing an 8:45

00:44:47.750 --> 00:44:51.170
show at Cafe Carlyle, and then
a midnight show at Joe's Pub

00:44:51.170 --> 00:44:52.550
every night for two weeks.

00:44:52.550 --> 00:44:56.750
So, I feel like I'm downtown
boy living in an uptown world.

00:44:56.750 --> 00:44:58.070
[LAUGHTER]

00:44:58.070 --> 00:44:59.960
So that'll be the
next thing that I'll

00:44:59.960 --> 00:45:02.950
be performing here in New
York, and on some dates

00:45:02.950 --> 00:45:05.420
throughout around America.

00:45:05.420 --> 00:45:09.470
And then after the middle of
July, it's kind of all on hold.

00:45:09.470 --> 00:45:13.980
I've got a few gigs,
actually, on weekends.

00:45:16.760 --> 00:45:18.590
There's ones like
the Kennedy Center.

00:45:18.590 --> 00:45:19.900
You can't turn down
the Kennedy Center.

00:45:19.900 --> 00:45:22.316
MICHAEL RAUCH: You can't turn
down the Kennedy Center, no.

00:45:22.316 --> 00:45:26.300
ALAN CUMMING: But in terms
of plays, there's nothing--

00:45:26.300 --> 00:45:30.211
there's a couple of things I'm
sort of loosely attached to.

00:45:30.211 --> 00:45:31.960
And there's definitely
people, like John--

00:45:31.960 --> 00:45:34.004
talking about
"Macbeth"-- oh, you were.

00:45:34.004 --> 00:45:35.420
John Tiffany, one
of the directors

00:45:35.420 --> 00:45:37.610
of that, who is here
in town, actually,

00:45:37.610 --> 00:45:40.680
is just directing that Harry
Potter play that's coming on.

00:45:40.680 --> 00:45:41.370
I just love him.

00:45:41.370 --> 00:45:42.750
We've done a few shows together.

00:45:42.750 --> 00:45:45.570
He's in "The Bacchae" that I
did when I played Dionysus.

00:45:45.570 --> 00:45:48.870
And I just really want to
do something with him again.

00:45:48.870 --> 00:45:50.530
It's been a few
years now, and I feel

00:45:50.530 --> 00:45:54.750
I haven't actually got
anything in the works with him.

00:45:54.750 --> 00:45:58.650
And so I kind of miss
that sort of urgency.

00:45:58.650 --> 00:46:03.150
But yeah, you know, it's
definitely in my periphery

00:46:03.150 --> 00:46:04.690
that I'll be back on stage.

00:46:04.690 --> 00:46:06.630
AUDIENCE: Well, we can't wait
to see you on a bigger stage

00:46:06.630 --> 00:46:07.005
again.

00:46:07.005 --> 00:46:08.004
ALAN CUMMING: Thank you.

00:46:11.120 --> 00:46:12.394
Oh, there's one more.

00:46:12.394 --> 00:46:13.560
MISTRAL MYERS: One more, oh.

00:46:13.560 --> 00:46:15.101
AUDIENCE: So, this
one's for Michael.

00:46:15.101 --> 00:46:17.640
But Alan, I have to say, you're
one of my favorite people

00:46:17.640 --> 00:46:18.690
to follow on Instagram.

00:46:18.690 --> 00:46:19.005
ALAN CUMMING: Oh, thanks.

00:46:19.005 --> 00:46:21.420
AUDIENCE: And I hope to
see at Club Cummings.

00:46:21.420 --> 00:46:23.724
ALAN CUMMING: Cumming,
Cumming, -ming, -ing, -ing.

00:46:23.724 --> 00:46:24.640
AUDIENCE: Oh, Cumming.

00:46:24.640 --> 00:46:26.570
Oh.

00:46:26.570 --> 00:46:30.390
So, in terms of writing
for a character where

00:46:30.390 --> 00:46:32.935
you know who the actor is,
what would you say are some

00:46:32.935 --> 00:46:34.560
of the cool parts of
that, and anything

00:46:34.560 --> 00:46:36.579
you need to be mindful of?

00:46:36.579 --> 00:46:38.370
MICHAEL RAUCH: I'll
answer the second part.

00:46:38.370 --> 00:46:40.170
I think being
mindful of not trying

00:46:40.170 --> 00:46:42.300
to repeat what you've
seen him do before

00:46:42.300 --> 00:46:44.760
and what you've fallen in
love with the actor doing,

00:46:44.760 --> 00:46:47.250
so you're not just going
down the easy route.

00:46:47.250 --> 00:46:50.620
But, you know, when I write,
I don't think of actors.

00:46:50.620 --> 00:46:53.786
So I just create a
character and follow it.

00:46:53.786 --> 00:46:55.410
But to be able to
have someone in mind,

00:46:55.410 --> 00:47:00.825
and visualize them, and have an
idea of what their rhythm is.

00:47:00.825 --> 00:47:03.930
And, I mean, Alan was talking
about not having a process,

00:47:03.930 --> 00:47:07.050
and I respect that 100%.

00:47:07.050 --> 00:47:10.860
But someone with
that type of talent,

00:47:10.860 --> 00:47:13.110
there is a magic that happens.

00:47:13.110 --> 00:47:15.690
And you watch them
because there's

00:47:15.690 --> 00:47:19.990
something going on that
makes you need to watch them.

00:47:19.990 --> 00:47:21.000
And Alan has that.

00:47:21.000 --> 00:47:24.660
So, to be able write a
character and imagine them

00:47:24.660 --> 00:47:29.250
in a bespoke tweed suit
with a pocket square,

00:47:29.250 --> 00:47:31.107
and at the same
time pull out a gun,

00:47:31.107 --> 00:47:33.690
I don't think there's a lot of
people who could pull that off.

00:47:33.690 --> 00:47:35.190
So, I don't know
if I would have had

00:47:35.190 --> 00:47:40.110
the confidence to do that if
I didn't know it was Alan.

00:47:40.110 --> 00:47:41.500
I imagine Alan
dressed like that.

00:47:41.500 --> 00:47:44.722
In fact, we had this
Christmas party at CBS

00:47:44.722 --> 00:47:46.430
that we had to-- we
didn't have to go to,

00:47:46.430 --> 00:47:47.431
but you had to go to it.

00:47:47.431 --> 00:47:48.471
ALAN CUMMING: You had to.

00:47:48.471 --> 00:47:51.150
MICHAEL RAUCH: And we happened
to be shooting two blocks away

00:47:51.150 --> 00:47:54.240
from the party so that we could
get the actors to the party.

00:47:54.240 --> 00:47:56.724
So, we shooting
the finale, and it

00:47:56.724 --> 00:47:58.890
was really important to get
there at a certain time.

00:47:58.890 --> 00:48:00.120
And I just said to Alan--

00:48:00.120 --> 00:48:02.370
he wrapped-- I was, like,
we're still shooting.

00:48:02.370 --> 00:48:04.320
I was like, listen, can
we get there quickly,

00:48:04.320 --> 00:48:05.700
can you just go
in your wardrobe.

00:48:05.700 --> 00:48:07.170
You know, he's wearing
this beautiful suit

00:48:07.170 --> 00:48:08.280
and these great shoes.

00:48:08.280 --> 00:48:11.224
And he was like, I'd rather
just get in my clothes.

00:48:11.224 --> 00:48:12.640
I was like, what's
the difference,

00:48:12.640 --> 00:48:13.950
you're in this beautiful suit.

00:48:13.950 --> 00:48:15.250
And he was like, let
me just quickly change.

00:48:15.250 --> 00:48:16.500
So he quickly changes.

00:48:16.500 --> 00:48:19.127
And all of a sudden, it's a
totally different human being.

00:48:19.127 --> 00:48:20.460
And I forgot that that was Alan.

00:48:20.460 --> 00:48:22.680
You know, with his spiky
hair, and a t-shirt,

00:48:22.680 --> 00:48:24.000
and these great pants.

00:48:24.000 --> 00:48:28.660
And so, I imagined the other
guy, and Alan became that guy.

00:48:28.660 --> 00:48:32.610
And so it just became a
much more enjoyable way

00:48:32.610 --> 00:48:33.470
to think about it.

00:48:33.470 --> 00:48:34.610
Do you write?

00:48:34.610 --> 00:48:35.340
AUDIENCE: No, no.

00:48:35.340 --> 00:48:35.850
I'm just interested.

00:48:35.850 --> 00:48:36.360
MICHAEL RAUCH: You
know, you're just

00:48:36.360 --> 00:48:37.550
trying to figure out
when you're coming up

00:48:37.550 --> 00:48:39.966
with a character all these
little different parts of them.

00:48:39.966 --> 00:48:41.910
And when you have a
head start, especially

00:48:41.910 --> 00:48:44.464
this type of head start, it
makes it much more enjoyable.

00:48:44.464 --> 00:48:46.880
ALAN CUMMING: And I think it's
funny as well that I feel--

00:48:46.880 --> 00:48:51.210
obviously, I sound and look
very different to the person

00:48:51.210 --> 00:48:52.980
you saw earlier on the screen.

00:48:52.980 --> 00:48:56.265
And we haven't shot it, we
were finished in December.

00:48:56.265 --> 00:48:58.890
So it's like a couple of months
now, a few months away from it.

00:48:58.890 --> 00:49:00.220
I've done other
things in between.

00:49:00.220 --> 00:49:02.803
That it's actually crazy-- like,
just today, doing talk shows,

00:49:02.803 --> 00:49:05.250
they play a little
clips of the show.

00:49:05.250 --> 00:49:07.110
And I'm like, oh,
yeah, that's funny.

00:49:07.110 --> 00:49:08.110
Oh, I forgot about that.

00:49:08.110 --> 00:49:10.680
And actually, when you're
in it, it's so easy,

00:49:10.680 --> 00:49:13.077
and kind of you're
just that person,

00:49:13.077 --> 00:49:14.910
and you know that you
have all these traits,

00:49:14.910 --> 00:49:16.159
and you have all these things.

00:49:16.159 --> 00:49:18.139
And actually standing
apart from it,

00:49:18.139 --> 00:49:20.305
it's sort of, you look back
and think, I don't-- oh,

00:49:20.305 --> 00:49:22.049
I can't remember
what that was like.

00:49:22.049 --> 00:49:24.090
But the great thing about
this character, I feel,

00:49:24.090 --> 00:49:29.327
is that there's a multitude
of different layers.

00:49:29.327 --> 00:49:31.410
It's actually something
I'm really looking forward

00:49:31.410 --> 00:49:34.650
to going back to explore more.

00:49:34.650 --> 00:49:37.880
I think there's a lot of
stuff that we could do.

00:49:37.880 --> 00:49:39.840
And that's really
exciting to me, to go back

00:49:39.840 --> 00:49:41.410
and try and do that.

00:49:41.410 --> 00:49:43.300
MICHAEL RAUCH: He's
very stuffy in the show.

00:49:43.300 --> 00:49:46.710
And it just brings
so much comedy

00:49:46.710 --> 00:49:49.110
to see him be stuffy
and unhappy about when

00:49:49.110 --> 00:49:50.440
things don't go his way.

00:49:50.440 --> 00:49:52.262
And it's so unlike
how he is in real life

00:49:52.262 --> 00:49:53.970
that you just want to
keep writing to it,

00:49:53.970 --> 00:49:56.287
because it's so absurd to
get to see him do that.

